T1  - Market microstructure and asset pricing: An empirical investigation of NYSE and NASDAQ securities
AU  - Reinganum, Marc R.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 28
IS  - 1
SP  - 127
EP  - 147
PY  - 1990
DA  - 1990/11/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(90)90050-A
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X9090050A
AB  - This research investigates the influence of market microstructure on liquidity premiums. Premiums of a competitive, multiple-dealership market (NASDAQ) are contrasted with those of a monopolistic, specialist system (NYSE). Differences in liquidity premiums are estimated from monthly stock returns. For small firms, the average returns of NYSE securities exceed the average returns of NASDAQ securities. This return differential persists after controlling for size, risk, and liquidity-related variables. Neither the NYSE nor NASDAQ dominates the other in providing liquidity. The NASDAQ appears to have a liquidity advantage over the NYSE for small firms but not for large companies.
